PNMP came after Yarn Plug'n'Play.
It also supports Plug'n'Play,
but it also has its own way of fixing the phantom dependencies issue
while still using node_modules and regular node module resolution.

It does this by hiding the dependencies node shouldn't resolve in node_modules/.pnpm.

Notice that it doesn't resolve `is-number`, which is a dependency of `is-odd`.
However, it does resolve the distant dependency!
So, it isn't perfect. You can still get unrelated dependencies sneaking in from parent directories.

Run these like this:

```
corepack pnpm install

# works
node 1-use-direct-dependency.js
node 3-use-distant-node-module.js

# fails
node 2-use-indirect-dependency.js
```
